		<a name="top" id="top"></a>
		<div id="siteNotice"><script type='text/javascript'>if (wgNotice != '') document.writeln(wgNotice);</script></div>		<h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading">Electronic stability control</h1>
		<div id="bodyContent">
			<h3 id="siteSub">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</h3>
			<div id="contentSub"></div>
									<div id="jump-to-nav">Jump to: <a href="#column-one">navigation</a>, <a href="#searchInput">search</a></div>			<!-- start content -->
			<p><b>Electronic stability control</b> (<b>ESC</b>) is a computerized technology that improves the safety of a <a href="/wiki/Car_handling" title="Car handling">vehicle's handling</a> by detecting and preventing skids. When ESC detects loss of steering control, ESC automatically applies individual brakes to help "steer" the vehicle where the driver wants to go. Braking is automatically applied to individual wheels, such as the outer front wheel to counter <a href="/wiki/Oversteer" title="Oversteer">oversteer</a>, or the inner rear wheel to counter <a href="/wiki/Understeer" title="Understeer">understeer</a>. Some ESC systems also reduce engine power until control is regained.<sup id="cite_ref-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
